We have some breaking changes between our old and new testnet and we would like to have a single API that support both testnet.

But seems like the filterVersions is not been called on user provided types and we cannot know which types without knowing the spec version first.

https://github.com/polkadot-js/api/blob/e6beb6554dff7ac61fd2e9d16b2631978e6ec626/packages/types-known/src/index.ts#L59-L62

For now we can use the chain name to distinguish between versions, but won't work once we introduce breaking changes in our public testnet via runtime upgrade.

We would like to pass something like this to API contractor and have it detect and use correct types based on spec version

```
export const typeChain: Record<string, OverrideVersionedType[]> = {
  acala: [
    {
      minmax: [undefined, 403],
      types: {
        Weight: 'u32'
      }
    }
  ]
};
```

This needs to go after https://github.com/polkadot-js/api/pull/1007

Basically, currently we only allow people to operate directly on the raw contract calls, i.e. https://github.com/polkadot-js/api/blob/master/packages/api/test/e2e/promise-contract.spec.ts#L92

In the above, we would really just like something along the following lines -

```js
import { Contract } from '@polkadot/api-contract';

await new Contract(<api instance>, <abi>, <addr>)
  .flip(<value to go along>, <max gas>, <...params>)
  .signAndSend(<account>, (submittableResult) => {...});
```

That is the end-result, earlier in the chain, we want to be able to deploy or attach code -

```js
import { Blueprint } from '@polkadot/api-contract';

// here it becomes a bit fuzzy... we need to 
//  - make the deploy call
//  - as a result, we want a Contract instance (previous code block)
//  - basically, it would take the address and abi to construct one
await new Blueprint(<api instance>, <abi>, <hash>)
  .deploy(<value>, <gas>, <...params>)
  .signAndSend(<account>, (submittableResult, contract) => {...});

// even better
const contract = await new Blueprint(...).deploy(<account>, ...);
```

Deployment of code (putCode) needs something similar -

```js
import { Code } from '@polkadot/api-contract';

// same as above with a bit of fuzziness
//  - as a result, we would like to retrieve a Blueprint instance
//  - basically it would take the retrieved hash and abi, to construct one
await new Code(<api instance>, <abi>, <wasm bytes>)
  .deploy(<endowment>, <max gas>)
  .signAndSend(<account>, (submittableResult, blueprint) => {...});

// even better
const blueprint = await new Code(...).deploy(<account>, ...);
```

So as a crazy code returns blueprint, returns contract, it ends up -

```js
const blueprint = await new Code(...).deploy(<account>, ...);
const contract = await blueprint.deploy(<account>, ...);

await contract
  .flip(<value to go along>, <max gas>, <...params>)
  .signAndSend(<account>, (submittableResult) => {...});
```

... or something like that

All-in-all, needs some playing to see what works and what doesn't, how to integrate and how to return values. Basically we want to move away from people having to manually inspect events, we can just handle all that transparently and have explicit interfaces.

Additionally, need to see how we tie this to all the type of api interfaces we are supporting, current RxJs & Promise (Similar approach as in Submittables?)

