Currently API routers are responsible for transforming requests based upon API version, however this has lead to host specific details leaking into the http router.
We also don't really want API version specific details leaking into the implementation.

I propose that we add a shim here so that transformations can be made after the request is routed.
This could look something like:

```go
// the API router
func(r *fooRouter) createFoo(ctx context.Context, w http.Response, req *http.Request) {
  // make a fooConfig from the reuqest
  r.backend.Create(ctx, fooConfig)
}
```

```go
func(b *fooBackend) Create(ctx context.Context, fooConfig Config) {
    b.transform.Create(ctx, &fooConfig)
}
```

```go
func(t *fooTransformer) Create(ctx context.Context, fooConfig) {
  ver := getApiVersion(ctx)
  if ver.LessThan("1.2") {
      // set some value
  }
}
```

Then the transformer can be configured with host specific details rather than relying on the HTTP router to have these details.
It also seems like it makes it easier to unit test such transformations.

Basically https://github.com/docker/docker/blob/master/api/server/httputils/errors.go#L52 has gone on far too long.

To replace this, we've tried a couple of different approaches which were pretty disastrous:

- errcode, which while there's nothing wrong with the errcode package, we used it horribly wrong and for the wrong reasons.
- HTTP errors package - https://github.com/docker/docker/blob/master/api/errors/errors.go#L13

errcode was a neat concept but in practice was misused and made the entire codebase just became absolutely horrible to work on where as before the horribleness was contained to just the API layer.

This lead to the http errors package currently in use for certain cases. This also seems like an "ok" thing, but in practice is also not really used correctly and generally more of a shortcut to correct error handling. We end up with low-level bits worried about HTTP status codes.

We need to standardize on a way to handle errors in the API. This potentially needs to be regardless of how the request came in (HTTP, GRPC, or even a direct function call...e.g. cluster->daemon).

The goal of good error handling is that the caller knows, or at least knows how to find out, the class of error that occurred so that the error can be dealt with appropriately. This is true of function calls and it is true across the "remote" API barrier.

### Goals

- API backends (e.g. `daemon`) should ideally not be concerned with HTTP.
- API clients should be able to read a returned error and be able to know *what* an error is.
- Reduce the cognitive overhead in trying to determine how to return an error
i. Example, what status code? (400, 409, 422, 412)
ii. How do I get the API to produce that status code I expect?
iii. How would non-remote API callers handle my error?
- Ensure status codes don't change because of either a change to the error text, or hopefully even a change to the low-level error type.

The way I see it there are really two ways to deal with this (in no particular order):

### Error class defined in common API package

This means in the API package we define several error classes like so (psuedo-code):

```go
package api

type Error interface {
    error
    NotFound() bool
    // other fn's for conflict, invalid arg, etc
}

type apiError struct { 
    err error
    notFound bool
    conflict bool
    invalidArg bool
}

func (e *apiError) Error() string { return e.err.Error() }
func (e *apiError) NotFound() bool { return e.notFound }

func NewNotFoundError(err error) Error {
    return &apiError{err: err, notFound: true}
}
```

From here the HTTP layer can determine both the error message and the class of error (not found) and the status code to return.

This approach is similar to the current approach we have except it's moving the http handling to the http layer and non-http code can just deal with this error type.

Another slight alternative but generally the same thing to this would be to use the well defined grpc error codes instead of defining our own. This could fit in well since part of the daemon is already using grpc anyway.

### Define error handling interfaces on backends

In this method, backends would be required to define a set of functions for error handling:

Example:

```go
package api

type ErrorInspector interface {
    IsNotFound(error) bool
    IsConflict(error) bool
    IsInvalidArgument(error) bool
}
```

```go
package container // container router

import "github.com/docker/docker/api"

type ContainerBackend interface {
    CreateContainer(...) error
    DeleteContainer(...) error
    api.ErrorInspector
}

func(r *containerRouter) getContainer(w http.ResponseWriter, req *http.Request) error {
    err := r.backend.DeleteContainer(...)
    if err != nil {
        if r.backend.IsNotFound(err) {
           // make an HTTP 404
       }
       // make an HTTP 500 probably
    }

    // normal
}
```

Writing out the above it seems a little risky since it requires the router to know the failure-modes of the backend. Maybe could be cleaned up a bit.


Interested in your thoughts, other alternatives, etc.

